As it became clear the South Vietnamese security forces would not provide adequate security for the US Air Force bases in Southeast Asia, President Lyndon Johnson authorized the beginning of the ground war.

As troop morale declined, US generals began to advocate for a more aggressive strategy to take the war to the NLF, abandoning the idea that South Vietnam could take back the North without US assistance.
A truce normally marked the Lunar New Year (Tet), but in 1968, the NLF broke the truce in order to launch the largest battle of the war - The Tet Offensive.

The Nixon Doctrine called for the bolstering of the Army of the Republic of Vietnam in order for them to take over the defense of South Vietnam. However, their efforts eventually prove to be in vain, leading to the evacuation of the US and South Vietnamese forces in the Fall of Saigon.
During the course of the war, the NLF captured thousands of US soldiers, some of whom were never recovered. Their recovery was used as part of Nixon's justification for continuing the war.

The political costs for the war began to add up for the Nixon Administration, and the South Vietnamese were now on their own. The American troops were home, but there was little celebration. The scars of the war would linger in American culture for decades to come.

The suicide of a young woman raises questions about several other cases of a similar nature. Hu believes they may be on the trail of a serial killer. Bao tries to help her extended family through some tough times.

A wrinkle in the serial suicide case reveals a new connection to the missing Zhang, raising suspicions of corruption. Bao deals with a death in her extended family while helping Hu with the suicide case.

Hu asks Bao's friend Ani to help stop the Suicide Killer before he kills his next victim. Zhang is accused of another murder, forcing Hu to make a difficult decision.

Time is running out for Ani as the suicide killer refuses to reveal where she is. While Bao searches, Hu engages in a battle of wits with the killer.

The investigation into Detective Zhang's disappearance comes to a head when Hu is suspended for refusing to drop the case. Determined to learn the truth, she investigates on her own. Meanwhile Bao starts a missing persons charity and gets a client her first day.

Hu juggles the investigation into Zhang's disappearance, her mothers refusal to discuss her relationship with a male prostitute, and Bao's missing persons case. Meanwhile, Bao deals with the fallout of Shi-San's betrayal by his father.

Bao's missing persons case becomes complicated when it appears that identity theft is involved. Hu's investigation into Zhang's disappearance results in one officer dead, the other injured, and no closer to the truth.
The final pieces of the investigation into Officer Zhang's disappearance fall into place. Bao and Hu race to rescue Zhang before his abductor finishes him off.
Zhang has been rescued, and his abductor has been revealed as Dai Wei, Hu's partner. Now she must get a confession while dealing with a horrible betrayal.

In November 795 UC, Kircheis arrives in the artificial resort satellite Kreuznach III for a vacation, as instructed by Reinhard, who had to remain in the Imperial capital Odin to prepare for his receiving of the countship of Lohengramm.

Kircheis is introduced by Michael von Keyserling to his old friend Christoph von Basel, a retired Vice Admiral. Kircheis notes that Basel continues to claim that he and his wife have only just arrived instead of the day before.
Despite admitting to Kircheis his awareness of Christoph von Basel's role as the leader of a thyoxin trafficking organisation, Michael von Keyserling refuses to testify against him.

The Battle of Van-Fleet Starzone continues with both sides locked in a stalemate. Mückenberger, viewing the Grimmelshausen Fleet as a liability, has ordered it to reorganise itself at the second satellite of the planet orbiting Van-Fleet.
On 21 March 794 UC, Imperial forces under the overall command of Gregor von Mückenberger invade the Van-Fleet Starzone and engage with Alliance forces commanded by Lasalle Lobos.

Schönkopf, worried that his superior Wahnschaffe, the regimental commander of the Rosen Ritter who is leading the Alliance reconnaissance mission, might have encountered Imperial forces, sets off with his trusted subordinates to find him.

The Imperial attack on the Alliance rear support base continues. Despite inflicting heavy losses on the Alliance forces, the Imperial forces are unable to break through the Alliance defensive line easily due to unfavourable geography.

The Imperial forces attacking the Alliance rear support base succeeds in breaking into the base headquarters, inflicting heavy damage to it. Reinhard manages to capture the Alliance base commander, Sinclair Cerebrese, alive

Lüneburg pays a visit with his wife Elisabeth to High Admiral Ovlesser, the commander of the Imperial Army, ostensibly as a formality marking his promotion to Rear Admiral but is in fact trying to lobby for support against Reinhard.

On 26 September 794 UC, Reinhard and Kircheis arrive at Iserlohn Fortress. Reinhard's squadron of over 1000 ships will be part of the forces facing the expected large-scale assault by the Free Planets Alliance on Iserlohn Fortress.

Kircheis returns to his hometown for a short trip to visit his parents, whom he has not met for eight years since joining the military. During his trip, he reminisces about his childhood and unexpectedly meets up with an old acquaintance.
Reinhard attends a party celebrating Richard von Grimmelshausen's recent promotion to Admiral. In the party, he clashes with Hermann von Lüneburg and almost gets into a fistfight with him.

The Sixth Battle of Iserlohn begins. The Alliance forces proceeds with Holland's plan of using the main fleet as a diversion to keep the attention of the Imperial forces and allow Holland's squadron to close in to Iserlohn Fortress.

Battle of Iserlohn turns into a battle of attrition. Yang Wenli feels that the Alliance forces should have retreated by this point. His concerns however are not shared by the Alliance commanders, who still adopt a wait-and-see attitude.
